It is better to take it in the simpler sense to which the rhythm leads us, ‘felix, notaque, et artium gratarum facies? ⁴ Nota' will then mean (as Schiitz) that her beauty was recognized, she was a general ‘toast‚’ ‘publica cura‚' Od. 2. 8. 8. With ‘artium facies’ cp. ‘centum puer artium’ 4. 1. 15. In speaking of ‘ winsome wiles‚’ his mind is perhaps going back to the wiles, which now are not winsome, of one who ‘vult formosa videri! ODE XIV

‘How can senate and people worthily honour thy virtues, Augustus, and transmit their memory to all time? The triumphs of the Nero brothers-of Drusus over the Vindelici, Genauni, and Breuni, of Tiberius over the Raeti-are all owing to thy auspices. How terrible was Tiberius in the pursuit3 as the south wind on the waters, or as the river Aufidus when it pours in a torrent from the hills down on the plain! Thine were the plan and provision of the campaign, thine its divinely-ordered success, for the victory came on a day already noteworthy for thy happy fortune—just fifteen years aster the capture of Alexandria. Thy reign has been a series of triumphs, and now all the world is at thy feet?
